SIMPLE: town
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Town
<hw>Town</hw> <pr>(toun)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>toun</ets>,
<ets>tun</ets>, AS. <ets>tun</ets> inclosure, fence, village, town; akin
to D. <ets>tuin</ets> a garden, G. <ets>zaun</ets> a hadge, fence, OHG.
<ets>zun</ets>, Icel. <ets>tun</ets> an inclosure, homestead, house, Ir.
& Gael. <ets>dun</ets> a fortress, W. <ets>din</ets>. Cf. <er>Down</er>,
<pos>adv. & prep.</pos>, <er>Dune</er>, <er>tine</er> to inclose.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Formerly: <sd>(a)</sd> An inclosure which surrounded
the mere homestead or dwelling of the lord of the manor.
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> The whole of the land which constituted
the domain. <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sd>(c)</sd> A collection of houses
inclosed by fences or walls.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Palsgrave.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any number or collection of houses to which belongs
a regular market, and which is not a city or the see of a bishop.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any collection of houses larger than a village, and
not incorporated as a city; also, loosely, any large, closely populated
place, whether incorporated or not, in distinction from the country, or
from rural communities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God made the country, and man made the <qex>town</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The body of inhabitants resident in a town; <as>as,
the <ex>town</ex> voted to send two representatives to the legislature;
the <ex>town</ex> voted to lay a tax for repairing the
highways</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A township; the whole territory within certain
limits, less than those of a country.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The court end of London; -- commonly with
<xex>the</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The metropolis or its inhabitants; <as>as, in winter
the gentleman lives in <ex>town</ex>; in summer, in the
country</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Always hankering after the diversions of the <qex>town</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stunned with his giddy larum half the <qex>town</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The same form of expressions is used in regard to other
populous towns.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A farm or farmstead; also, a court or
farmyard.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Town</xex> is often used adjectively or in
combination with other words; as, <xex>town</xex> clerk, or
<xex>town</xex>-clerk; <xex>town</xex>-crier, or <xex>town</xex> crier;
<xex>town</xex>hall, <xex>town</xex>-hall, or <xex>town</xex> hall;
<xex>town</xex>house, <xex>town</xex> house, or
<xex>town</xex>-house.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Village; hamlet. See <er>Village</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Town clerk</b></col>, <cd>an office who keeps the records
of a town, and enters its official proceedings. See <er>Clerk</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Town cress</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the garden cress,
or peppergrass.</cd> <au>Dr. Prior.</au> -- <col><b>Town
house</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A house in town, in distinction from a
house in the country.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>See <er>Townhouse</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Town meeting</b></col>, <cd>a legal meeting of the
inhabitants of a town entitled to vote, for the transaction of public
bisiness.</cd> <mark>[U. S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Town talk</b></col>,
<cd>the common talk of a place; the subject or topic of common
conversation.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>town and gown</ent>⟦br⟧
